Notes from the field: A lovely Saturday morning here in Austin.  I am on day three stretching before we go on a family run. On my first cobra stretch I look down to see something under the mat and discover old dried ferret poop.(I store my yoga mat in a corner in a bag with my weights pad, but who knows what goes on in the corner by the couch.)  I peel that off and calmly place on the tile floor and ask oldest daughter to come remove it. Later when you are discussing spreading honey on my mid torso I hear something thump next to me. Day 3... After missing two days of this series (I still did morning yoga on Friday and bedtime yoga yesterday). Today I observed... a lot of anger. With each pose and each breath I felt it and to be honest, I wasn't fully present through this. The last two days have been tough. On Friday I was in a very minor car accident. It snowed (it rarely snows where I'm from) and I slipped into a ditch. Physically, I am fine. Mentally and emotionally, I am shaken up. Despite the fact it was minor it added a layer of anxiety to the past two days. After someone pulled me out of the ditch and I got home, and then tried to venture out a few hours later to get to work (even though I'd be 4 hours late) and I find out I did more damage than initially anticipated. I could continue with the play-by-play but long story short, I have been stressed. I did it though and I made it and I observed that it was not anxiety I have been feeling today but anger. Hopefully that recognition will let me release and when I come back tomorrow, or maybe it won't be until day 6 or 7, I will be able to reconnect with my body and experience how amazing I felt after day 2s practice. Time will tell. Thank you for these, Adriene, and for your kind words through the practices.

I started Sunday, so I‚Äôm only on Day 3, but had a fascinating experience near the end of it. I‚Äôve always been shaky with tree poses, definitely opting for the ‚Äútoe on the ground version‚Äù...and stumbling a few times with that as well...but doing my best not to look down. I challenge myself to raise my gaze higher, and my eyes go to the mirror on the wall facing me. It‚Äôs an old-style mirror, with a mirrored rim around the outside, so above my reflection is another strip of reflection that is slightly off from the main one (wow, I hope you can make sense of this). The mirror is lowish (no, I‚Äôm tallish), and so what I see when I raise my gaze is my eyes looking at me from that narrow strip...but the eyes looking at me are also exactly where my third eye would be in the main reflection, if the mirror was just a bit higher on the wall. So I am looking at myself from my third eye. And suddenly my whole body relaxes into the tree position and I find my balance. I was able to breathe comfortably, and was even able to raise my toe for part of the time. Pretty poignant experience. Thank you, Adriene!

What a thrill to see that 1,394 yogis-in-training accompanied me this morning as I observed the sun rising over Tokyo along with this beautiful Day 3 practice. I am a couple of days behind because my college-age son, who has been struggling with stress and anxiety, checked himself into the hospital, afraid that he may not be able to go on. This is a child who had always done everything "right" -- and ironically, as his academic star continues to rise, he finds himself increasingly unhappy. I want to rush to him, to be by his side, but he has asked to take this journey alone: some time on his own, with none of the noise of school, friends or family, or his devices, to get grounded and find his inner peace. I am grateful to anyone who reads this -- you are among the first that I have told of my deep, quiet grief and worry. Tears shed on the mat this morning, but I feel ready to face another day. Sending this peace out to my son, and to any of you that are similarly struggling. Namaste.

I think dwelling on this dual state of observer and observed gives us so much power. Cognitively, it gives us the freedom to analyze our own actions and check our biases. Emotionally/spiritually, it gives us the capacity to have empathy for ourselves, which in turn gives us  empathy for others. Physically, it allows us to be honest with ourselves about what feels good, and to adjust accordingly. Socially, we can appreciate that everyone around us has the same experience of being observer and observed, narrative and action, and we can suddenly relate to those who have had completely different life experiences. Observation is freedom.

Did not feel like getting started on Day 3 but felt great towards the end of it. I made sure I was a tad more mindful this time around during my poses. During this year I found out that I was hurting my elbows during yoga. It turns out that I hyperextend them during planks or downward dogs. Apparently if you keep your biceps contracted it prevents hyperextension. So I was mindful of where I was active within my body. By observing I notice that my mind is a little more silent and that I was very much in the moment and I feel rejuvenated from my day thus far.

I failed a lot today. I started with a bad attitude and was only noticing my belly fat, thinking about all the things I have to get done today, etc. My muscles were weak and I am simply very out of shape this winter. There were multiple times I had to go to child's pose or mountain pose for a break. It's easy to feel like a failure because of that. BUT I still went through to the end. In the past as soon as I'm unable to do a pose or 2, I quit the video and say "I'll try another day". But guess what? I don't come back the next day then. 
It's important to remember that it's not about doing everything perfectly but what is an improvement for yourself. Even though I felt like I was "lazy and couldn't discipline myself enough to finish poses", I did stay to the end of the video, and my muscles are shaking which means I DID work hard. Don't compare yourself to others, your body is at a different place and you just might not be able to hold a pose at this point - that is NOT giving up. What's giving up is not showing up again tomorrow because of that. If you feel it in your muscles afterward, if you feel mentally clearer afterward, even if you still feel like crap but completed the video, you did not waste your time. You will come back tomorrow, and you will gradually improve. This is only the beginning, and like Adrienne says, the most important thing is to keep showing up.

Yoga allows me to assess and improve my body mechanics, what I often refer to kinematics (something I became more aware of during my 3D modeling days when animation had to work out inverse kinematics).  For that to be effective, I have to listen honestly, which in turn, requires a bit of humility and curiosity.  The conscious mind can be (and usually is) very distracting to that listening. And I have a very busy conscious mind. I think that Adriene does a great job of showing us of what we should be listening to and for, both mechanically, and spiritually. If I find her jokes annoying, or I find her references too "girly," i have to remind myself that while that may be true, it really just means that I'm not paying enough attention to what I should be, that I have to get past all that, and remember who the teacher is and why I'm trying to be a student in the first place.  I've done yoga before, and I got back into it a few years ago when I discovered 30 Days of Yoga‚Äã. I stuck with it, and was impressed at what I got out of it. 

I have to be in the right mindset in order to successfully practice yoga. But that's the point. If my recovery was just about physical therapy, I'd be outside jogging, or hitting the gym.  But my body isn't quite ready for that. You can't race a car that's hasn't been tuned, not without ruining it. I can't just assume that there's something wrong with me. I need to listen quietly to find out what is wrong.  Mentally, that's a challenge. But physiologically, there are tangible signs. Like how I breathe through certain movements, or how my body feels while doing them. I can "feel" those symptoms. If I'm tight, I can loosen up. And, as each day passes, with each session, I can feel the improvement. The downward dog I am cringing through today will feel more natural (hopefully) next week.  My conscious breathing now should eventually feel more natural and intuitive later.  The steps that my mind has to go through to affect my body are the same steps that also affect my mind as well. As yoga gets easier and more comfortable, it should be easier to listen to myself, to listen to what's going on in my head, and not just my body.

Earlier, I described the difference between want and need. Want is something you can usually identify pretty quickly, with a pretty strong emotional response. Desire.  Need usually isn't so easily obvious. Want is identified by the conscious mind. Need is defined by the subconscious programming. We want a million dollars, but we need air to breathe. With a busy/distracted mind, we often confuse need with want, necessity with desire.  And there is nothing wrong with want, as long as needs are being met.

I want to run again. I want to climb rocks and fall out of trees again. I want to rebuild my motorcycle without being too exhausted or in too much pain. I want to go skydiving with my 360 camera. The frustrations of my current limitations make those wants feel like needs, because my physicality defines who I am as a person. But before any of that can happen, needs have to be met. My body needs to heal properly. And my mind has to be open, patient and willing for that process. Yoga alone isn't got to "fix" me. But it helps me find the mindset I need to choose the right path. It allows me to work past the frustrations and desires and distractions, and focus on what actually needs to be done first. 

So far, it's only Day 3, and as you can tell from this post, the brain is still busy as ever. It's still an effort to tune out the noise and tune into the practice. It's still not as fun as I remember it in the past. The future still seems so impossibly far away. But I still got up this morning and hit PLAY. I groaned, I laughed, with both Adriene and at myself. I'm taking notes. I falling out and catching back up. I am realizing. While other F words come to mind, I will say that I am finding the Fun in this daily challenge. And I look forward to taking what I'm learning it, and exercising it throughout my day, until tomorrow, Day 4. In the meantime, I'm celebrating surviving this episode with a shot of Fireball.  Happy Friday, peeps!

You made me fall in love with yoga. All those years I have been trying different types of exercise. And quitting them. Because the motivation was always something outside me. I wanted more definition, better looking body, more flexibility‚Ä¶the exercise was just a means to a goal. For the first time ever I am coming back to my mat each day without trying to do more, be more, achieve more, be better, be something that I am not. For the first time the purpose is yoga itself. The purpose is being in the present moment as it is, which is love. I don‚Äôt think I would gain this perspective without you. Because human beings can use even such a beautiful thing as yoga as a way of forcing, trying hard, judging what is, judging the body, its flexibility and strength. With your guidance I learned to bring all of myself to the mat. To allow all what is coming up, whether it is good, bad or ugly:-)To witness it, welcome it and love it. To fully experience the moment and its fullness. The abundance of all things. Strength and flexibility are just icing on a cake. But it is journey that matters. Thank you Adriene, my teacher:-)
